#--: Generators

TODO: no 'next' method on iterators? Just a normal instance that has a 'call'
method that returns the values and optionally takes args? Always (?) returns an
optional? The 'call' method name itself can be sugared away... YES

TODO: this needs to be checked over.... Compiler will automatically construct a
class definition that will implement the iterator protocol?

#code language=zerolang: """
  # iterator protocol looks like this:
  # (better names for arguments?)
  # givetype is always an Optional to allow end of stream to be signalled...
  # 'call' return value is always borrowed (use a normal function if you 
  #   want to generate a stream of owned values)

  iterator: protocol {
    # ownership of 'givetype' (taken or borrowed) cannot be specified?
    givetype: any.generic       # 'default' generic type, must be specified
    taketype: any.generic.none  # defaults to none, can be left unspecified

    call: function { takes: taketype } out givetype.borrow
  }

  mytype: class {
      field: u32
      field2: u8

      create: function {field: u32 field2: u8} out this is {
          t: meta.create field: 0 field2: 0
          return t
      }

      each: function {t: this.lock avar: u8} out iterator subreftype is {
          # note that 'this' is locked... but iterator is owned by caller
          # 'avar' needs to become a field in the compiler generated iterator 
          #   object definition
          # yield can also be used as an expression returning a value if the 
          #   iterator 'givetype' is specified
          yield # ...
          yield # ...
          for x: subiterator {
              # no 'yield from' ??
              yield x
          }
          return  # can return to break early. Not required at end of function
                  # MUST have NO return value (effectively 'none'). Real return type
                  # of the generator (call()) is union {subreftype; none} or 
                  # optional subreftype)
      }

      each2: function {t: this.lock} out iterator subreftype is {
          # can also have no args. Skip 'in' entirely - NO, still need 'this'
          # just use normal functions if ownership needs to be given...
          yield # ...
      }
  }
  """

For function/yield implementation:
    
#ul:
  [#*: compiler must turn the iterator 'function' inside out and into a class]
  [#*: the 'each' call must always #~"lock" dependancies]
  [#*: compiler generated 'iterator' object is always a #~"class". It cannot be a
    valtype because it has identity (cannot be copied) and it has the locks
    associated with it. Can a #~"class" have no instance methods so it doesn't
    require an allocation?]
  [#*: the class will have all argument vars from the func converted to member
    fields]
  [#*: the class will have access to the parent's internal namespace by taking
    #~"this.private" as an arg in the constructor. ie. it is a 'friend' class of
    the parent]
  [#*: the class is NOT instantiable by user code (because of ownership binding
    to parent), it MUST be called via a for loop so compiler can enforce
    ownership/locking. NO - can be instantiated by user code]
  [#*: iterator instance has one method 'call' returning #~"union { none subtype }"
    (an Optional)]
  [#*: see Raymond Chen's article series on the implementation of iterators in
    C\# for an approach. Need switch/goto in generated C code
    #>"https://devblogs.microsoft.com/oldnewthing/20080812-00/?p=21273"]
  [#*: compare with channels. channels and iterators can be unified? How to
    enable streaming INTO a stream/generator? Just use function calls to push
    into streams.]
  [#*: generators can be generic? yes]
  [#*: a 'yield' method can also 'as' to another facet of the parent object (??? or
    only on return?). This could be useful for eg. objects that can only be
    streamed once (so on return would be better? otherwise need to check type
    after each value is yielded) NO, no flowtyping now...]
  [#*: integers have a builtin 'each' method that will iterate from 0 to n - 1? Yes.
    #~"for x: in 10 { ... }". The each on integers have 'from' (defaulting to 0)
    and 'step' (defaulting to 1) arguments? Step can be negative for
    decrementing? #~"for x: (10.each from: 6 step: 2) { ... }"]
  [#*: 'iterator' is a predefined generic type. It has 2 parameters, 'gives' and
    'takes'. 'gives' is the type that is yielded out to the caller each time.
    'takes' is the input type to the 'next' call on the iterator instance and
    defaults to 'none'.]

#code language=zerolang: """
  # use like (same syntax for iterators and generators for usage):
  # TODO: need to use 'with' for this one...
  for x: (mytypeinstance.each avar: 0) {
      # will call mytypeinstance.iterator and store the resulting iterator object
      # can have arguments as shown or can have no arguments...
      # then will call mytypeinstance.call at each iteration and bind to x
      # ownership of x is always borrowed
      # use x here; can't use mytypeinstance directly (locked)
      # iterator destroyed at end of scope
      # mytypeinstance is then available again outside this scope
  }

  # or ('each' is default iterator)
  for x: (mytypeinstance avar: 0) { }

  # or (arg is default so can be unnamed)
  for x: in mytypeinstance 0 { }

  for x: in mytypeinstance.each2 {  # no args is also allowed...
      # ...
  }

  # sugar to call 'default' iterator (when called exactly 'each') 
  #   ie. mytypeinstance.each
  for x: in mytypeinstance {  
      # ...
  }
  """

TODO: compare mytypeinstance is iterable (has .each) vs a variable/function 
that is an Option/Result? Must use #~"in" for the iterable otherwise need to 
explictly create (eg. with a #~"with" statement) and iterate (call) the 
result repeatedly

---

Type signatures examples for all Generator types. Each of these are compiler
generated (a function that returns these is converted into a state machine
object that functions as a Generator.

'Standard' iterable:

#code language=zerolang: """
  # 'standard' Iterable.
  # locks the parent object while in scope
  # iterator take no argument and returns a borrowed child element that 
  #  locks the iterator while in scope
  Iterable: class {
    # ... 'captured' local variables are stored here to maintain state 
    #  between calls.
    # ... the arguments to Iterable are also stored here. All MUST be locked.
  } as {
    create: function { 
      # if the Generator is a method, parent is stored... (.private.lock)
      parentiterable: parenttype.private.lock  
      arg1: xxy.lock
    } out this is {
      meta.create :parentiterable :arg1
    }

    
    call: function { t: this.private.lock } out xxxchild.borrow is {}
  }
  """

----

#code language=zerolang: """
  # a variant to modify the ownership of each Generator style
  # out = what is returned to the caller of the iterator
  # in = what is sent into the iterator from the caller
  GeneratorOwnership: variant {
    OutBorrowInBorrow: none # the default (and 'in' is usually none)
    OutBorrowInTake: none
    OutTakeInBorrow: none # returns an owned item
    OutTakeInTake: none
  }

  # xxx we can't control the outtype ownership (could be take or borrow),
  # so can't have an interface for Iterable?
  Iterable: protocol {
    call: function { 
      outtype: any.generic 
      intype: any.generic 
      ownership: GeneratorOwnership.generic.OutBorrowInBorrow 
      inval: intype  # can't control ownership take/borrow here
    } outval: outtype  # can't control ownership take/borrow here
  }
  """

Ok, assume we will always 'take' the 'in' parameter. In a Generator function,
it may be hard to release control of a 'borrowed' item before the next yield
because this is not controlled by scope. But a 'taken' param would need to be
careful too - would need to either store it locally ordispose of it before the
next 'yield' call. Maybe always store the parameter in the Iterator object,
desroying any previous one before replacing it?




#--: Iterators

#code language=zerolang: """
  myiterabletype: class {
    field: u32
    field2: u8
  } as {

    create: function {field: u32 field2: u8} out this is {
      # ...
      t: meta.create :field :field2
      return t
    }

    iterate: function { t: this.lock ivar: u8 } out mytypeiterator is {
      # 'this' in 'in' parameter MUST be locked to return the iterator below
      # (because it holds a lock over 'this' so must escape into an env that
      # also locks 'this')
      # so mytypeiterator returned holds lock over 'this'

      # iterator being returned is owned, so must be a localvar/takenparam
      # 't' is locked after this line
      i: mytypeiterator t.private ivar: ivar

      return i
    }

    iterate2: function { t: this.lock } out itersubtype is {
      # can have other iterator functions, but those not named 'iterate'
      # would need to be called explicitly
      # can also have no additional args in an iterator function
    }
  }

  mytypeiterator: class {
    # all iterators must be classes (reftypes) No, why?
    # the iterator (likely) needs to hold a reference to the iterable, so 
    #  this one needs to be a class to hold a reference to another class 
    #  instance
    state: int  # fields to maintain state of iterator here
    target: myiterabletype.private # do we need to specify private here?
  } as {

    # lock on 'target' type is required so it can be stored as a field
    create: function {target: mytype.private.lock ivar: u8 } out this is {
      t: meta.create state: 0 target: target
      return t
    }

    call: function { t: this.lock } out itersubtype.borrow is {
      # ...
      # must retain the lock over 'this' if we return a 'borrow'
      # return type could be 'taken' (if a new object is constructed - BUT 
      # then we don't need to lock 'this'!!!!) or borrowed
      # (if exposing an internal part of the parent object)
      i: t.target.index t.state # 'i' takes a lock over 't'
      t.state = t.state + 1
      return i
    }
  }
  """

For:

The labelled target of a #~"for" (if present) is examined:

- if it is a function or an object method, call it every iteration
- NOTE: the function/method is NOT immediately evaluated
- if it is an object instance with an #~"iterate" method, call that to get the
  iterator, then call that iterator on every iteration
- if it is an object instance with a #~"call" method (with or without arguments),
  call that every iteration (with the supplied arguments)
- ownership: the #~"for" exposes the correct ownership since the compiler will
  check the types in the 'call' method of the iterator. If a taken type is
  returned, it will be owned in the body of the #~"for". If borrowed, it will be
  borrowed in the body. 
- scoping in the body ends at the end of the loop or immediately after a break
  or continue. So a lock on the iterator held by the returned element will be
  released immediately before the start of the next loop so that the iterator
  is able to be called to return the next element (which itself will then take
  a lock for the loop body)

#code language=zerolang: """
  for x: myfunc loop {
    # x is set to myfunc result before every iteration
  }

  for x: myfunc2 myarg loop {
    # x is set to myfunc result before every iteration
    # function can have arguments
  }

  for x: (myfunc3 myarg name: mynamedarg) loop {
    # x is set to myfunc result before every iteration
    # function can have arguments, named arguments must be in parens
  }

  myobject: make_an_object_with_a_call_method
  for x: myobject loop {
    # x is set to myobject.call result before every iteration
  }

  myobject2: make_an_object_with_a_call_method_with_args
  for x: myobject2 myarg loop {
    # x is set to myobject2.call result before every iteration
    # 'call' can have arguments, 
    # named arguments must be in parens (not shown)
  }
  """

An iterable object:

#code language=zerolang: """
  # myiterable is an iterable object that has an 'iterate' method
  for x: myiterable loop {
    # the myiterable.iterate method is called (with no arguments) to 
    #   retrieve the iterator
    # x is set to the result of the iterator (called without args) 
    #   before every iteration
  }
  """

Any other iterables where the above does not apply, needs to be handled
manually with a preceeding #~"with" statement. eg:

- the iterable has both a 'call' method and a 'iterate' method and you want to
  'call' that object on each iteration (rather than 'iterate')
- the iterable's iterate method is not called 'iterate' (eg 'iterate2')
- the iterable's iterate method needs to take arguments
- the returned iterator needs to take arguments

#code language=zerolang: """
  # myiterable is an iterable object that has both a 'call' method 
  #  and an 'iterate' method
  for x: myiterable.call loop {
    # force the call on each loop (rather than calling 'iterate' to retrieve
    #  an iterator to use)
    # ...
  }

  # myiterable2 is an iterable object that has an 'iterate2' method
  with i: myiterable2.iterate2 do for x: i loop {
    # ...
  }

  # myiterable3 is an iterable object that has an 'iterate' method
  #  that requires arguments
  with i: myiterable3.iterate3 myarg do for x: i loop {
    # ...
  }

  # myiterable4 is an iterable object that has an 'iterate' method
  #  that requires arguments, and the resulting iterator also requires
  #  arguments
  with i: myiterable4.iterate4 myarg do for x: i myarg2 loop {
    # ...
  }
  """





