#--: IDEA: Type narrowing. Flow typing.

This is required for early exit with a guard clause for subpart1 of the type,
then continuing the function with subpart2 without wrapping the whole rest of
the function body in a 'match'.

Be sure to see the typescript page:
#>"https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/2/narrowing.html"

Narrowing should also happen when reassigning a var to a specific subtype.

typeof/instanceof guards are not required because top level union objects need
to be referenced by subtype name anyway (no common operations for unions, only
for protocols -- even methods defined directly on the union need to discern
subtypes in their method bodies)

Also: 

#ul:
    [#*: dead code warnings.]
    [#*: note that bools are unions too, so literal true vs false may also be
      detected]

Both #~"if" and #~"match" can be used for narrowing? Unions, variants provide
membership 'methods' that 'return' bool? NO, just #~"match"

Types of vars at each scope may need to store their 'type' and also excluded
'subtypes'. eg:

#code language=zerolang: """
  myenum: variant { :A :B :C }
  x = functhatreturns myenum  # note that if we set an explicit subtype here 
                  # (rather than a function call) then we would be able to narrow to 
                  # exactly that type...

  # outside, x 'type' is myenum, 'subtype' is not [] (empty list)
  match x case A {
      # x 'type' is myenum.A, 'subtype' is not []
      # ...
  } else {
      # x 'type' is myenum, 'subtype' is not [A]
  }
  # outside, x 'type' is myenum, 'subtype' is not [] (empty list)

  match f: open "filename.txt" case ok {
      # write file....
      # f is open file
  } case err {
      # print/re-raise error...
      # f is err
  }

  f: open "filename.txt"
  match f case err then {
      # handle error
      # f is accessible as error type here
      return # ...
  } # XXX: not exhaustive?
  # if there were an 'else' here, it would know f is a file 

  # for rest of function, f is accessible as file because err did early exit
  """

TODO: how to refer back to the original result union if we wanted to? Can't.
Just let narrowed result fall out of scope. Then original value is again
available (as long as it still exists)


